We are able to prove these results about the convergence of the geometric
 series because we can express the sum of the first 
\begin_inset Formula \( n \)
\end_inset 

 terms of the series in a simple expression.
 To see this, let 
\begin_inset Formula \( S_{n} \)
\end_inset 

 be the sum of the first 
\begin_inset Formula \( n \)
\end_inset 

 terms of the series, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{n}=1+x+x^{2}+x^{3}+\cdots +x^{n-1}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Multiply by 
\begin_inset Formula \( x \)
\end_inset 

